[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] The execution units, called *tasks*, are executed concurrently on one or more worker nodes using multiprocessing, eventlet or gevent.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] Tasks can execute asynchronously (in the background) or synchronously (wait until ready).
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] Celery is used in production systems, for services such as Instagram, to process millions of tasks every day.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] Celery is written in Python, but the protocol can be implemented in any language.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] It can also operate with other languages using webhooks.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] There is also a Ruby-Client called RCelery, a PHP client, a Go client, a Rust client, and a Node.js client.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] Celery requires a message broker to run.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] As of October 2024, Redis and RabbitMQ are supported and actively maintained and monitored.
[src:celery-tasks/celery-software] Amazon SQS is supported and maintained but does not support worker inspection and management at runtime, while Zookeeper and Kafka are currently in experimental development.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:celery-tasks/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] This document describes the current stable version of Celery (5.6).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Task queues are used as a mechanism to distribute work across threads or machines.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] A task queue’s input is a unit of work called a task.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Dedicated worker processes constantly monitor task queues for new work to perform.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Celery communicates via messages, usually using a broker to mediate between clients and workers.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] To initiate a task the client adds a message to the queue, the broker then delivers that message to a worker.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] A Celery system can consist of multiple workers and brokers, giving way to high availability and horizontal scaling.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] In addition to Python there’s node-celery for Node.js, a PHP client, gocelery, gopher-celery for Go, and rusty-celery for Rust.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Language interoperability can also be achieved exposing an HTTP endpoint and having a task that requests it (webhooks).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] The integration packages aren’t strictly necessary, but they can make development easier, and sometimes they add important hooks like closing database connections at *fork(2)*.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] You can install Celery either via the Python Package Index (PyPI) or from source.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Celery also defines a group of bundles that can be used to install Celery and the dependencies for a given feature.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] You can specify these in your requirements or on the **pip** command-line by using brackets.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] Multiple bundles can be specified by separating them by commas.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the `auth` security serializer.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the https://pypi.org/project/eventlet/ pool.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the https://pypi.org/project/gevent/ pool.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Redis as a message transport or as a result backend.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Amazon SQS as a message transport (*experimental*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the `task_remote_tracebacks` feature.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Memcached as a result backend (pure-Python implementation).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Apache Cassandra/Astra DB as a result backend with DataStax driver.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Couchbase as a result backend.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Elasticsearch as a result backend.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using AWS DynamoDB as a result backend.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using Zookeeper as a message transport.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using SQLAlchemy as a result backend (*supported*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the Pyro4 message transport (*experimental*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the SoftLayer Message Queue transport (*experimental*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the Consul.io Key/Value store as a message transport or result backend (*experimental*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] specifies the lowest version possible for Django support.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] You should probably not use this in your requirements, it’s here for informational purposes only.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the Google Cloud Storage as a result backend (*experimental*).
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] for using the Google Cloud Pub/Sub as a message transport (*experimental*)..
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] The last command must be executed as a privileged user if you aren’t currently using a virtualenv.
[src:celery-tasks/introduction] The Celery development version also requires the development versions of https://pypi.org/project/kombu/, https://pypi.org/project/amqp/, https://pypi.org/project/billiard/, and https://pypi.org/project/vine/.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] In computer science, **message queues** and **mailboxes** are software-engineering components typically used for inter-process communication (IPC), or for inter-thread communication within the same process.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] They use a queue for messaging – the passing of control or of content.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Group communication systems provide similar kinds of functionality.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The message queue paradigm is a sibling of the publisher/subscriber pattern, and is typically one part of a larger message-oriented middleware system.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Most messaging systems support both the publisher/subscriber and message queue models in their API, e.g.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Competing Consumers pattern enables multiple concurrent consumers to process messages on the same message queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Message queues implement an asynchronous communication pattern between two or more processes/threads whereby the sending and receiving party do not need to interact with the message queue at the same time.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Messages placed onto the queue are stored until the recipient retrieves them.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Message queues have implicit or explicit limits on the size of data that may be transmitted in a single message and the number of messages that may remain outstanding on the queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Many implementations of message queues function internally within an operating system or within an application.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Such queues exist for the purposes of that system only.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Other implementations allow the passing of messages between different computer systems, potentially connecting multiple applications and multiple operating systems.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] These message queuing systems typically provide resilience functionality to ensure that messages do not get "lost" in the event of a system failure.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Examples of commercial implementations of this kind of message queuing software (also known as message-oriented middleware) include IBM MQ (formerly MQ Series) and Oracle Advanced Queuing (AQ).
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] There is a Java standard called Java Message Service, which has several proprietary and free software implementations.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Real-time operating systems (RTOSes) such as VxWorks and QNX encourage the use of message queuing as the primary inter-process or inter-thread communication mechanism.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] This can result in integration between message passing and CPU scheduling.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Early examples of commercial RTOSes that encouraged a message-queue basis to inter-thread communication also include VRTX and pSOS+, both of which date to the early 1980s.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The Erlang programming language uses *processes* to provide concurrency; these processes communicate asynchronously using message queuing.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The message queue software can be either proprietary, open source or a mix of both.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] It is then run either on premise in private servers or on external cloud servers (message queuing service).
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Examples on hardware-based messaging middleware vendors are Solace, Apigee, and IBM MQ.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] In a typical message-queueing implementation, a system administrator installs and configures message-queueing software (a queue manager or broker), and defines a named message queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Or they register with a message queuing service.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] An application then registers a software routine that "listens" for messages placed onto the queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Second and subsequent applications may connect to the queue and transfer a message onto it.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The queue-manager software stores the messages until a receiving application connects and then calls the registered software routine.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The receiving application then processes the message in an appropriate manner.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] These are all considerations that can have substantial effects on transaction semantics, system reliability, and system efficiency.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Historically, message queuing has used proprietary, closed protocols, restricting the ability for different operating systems or programming languages to interact in a heterogeneous set of environments.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] An early attempt to make message queuing more ubiquitous was Sun Microsystems' JMS specification, which provided a Java-only abstraction of a client API.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] This allowed Java developers to switch between providers of message queuing in a fashion similar to that of developers using SQL databases.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] In practice, given the diversity of message queuing techniques and scenarios, this wasn't always as practical as it could be.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] These protocols are at different stages of standardization and adoption.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The first two operate at the same level as HTTP, MQTT at the level of TCP/IP.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Some proprietary implementations also use HTTP to provide message queuing by some implementations, such as Amazon's SQS.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] This is because it is always possible to layer asynchronous behaviour (which is what is required for message queuing) over a synchronous protocol using request-response semantics.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] However, such implementations are constrained by the underlying protocol in this case and may not be able to offer the full fidelity or set of options required in message passing above.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Many of the more widely known communications protocols in use operate synchronously.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The HTTP protocol – used in the World Wide Web and in web services – offers an obvious example where a user sends a request for a web page and then waits for a reply.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] However, scenarios exist in which synchronous behaviour is not appropriate.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] For example, AJAX (Asynchronous JavaScript and XML) can be used to asynchronously send text, JSON or XML messages to update part of a web page with more relevant information.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Google uses this approach for their Google Suggest, a search feature which sends the user's partially typed queries to Google's servers and returns a list of possible full queries the user might be interested in the process of typing.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] This list is asynchronously updated as the user types.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Other asynchronous examples exist in event notification systems and publish/subscribe systems.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] In both of the above examples it would not make sense for the sender of the information to have to wait if, for example, one of the recipients had crashed.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Applications need not be exclusively synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] In all these sorts of situations, having a subsystem which performs message-queuing (or alternatively, a broadcast messaging system) can help improve the behavior of the overall system.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] There are two common message queue implementations in UNIX.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] One is part of the SYS V API, the other one is part of POSIX.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] UNIX SYS V implements message passing by keeping an array of linked lists as message queues.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Each message queue is identified by its index in the array, and has a unique descriptor.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] A given index can have multiple possible descriptors.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] UNIX gives standard functions to access the message passing feature.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] This system call takes a key as an argument and returns a descriptor of the queue with the matching key if it exists.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] flag is set, it makes a new message queue with the given key and returns its descriptor.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Used to receive a message from a given queue descriptor.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The caller process must have read permissions for the queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Used to change message queue parameters like the owner.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] A message queue can be deleted only by its creator, owner, or the superuser.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The POSIX.1-2001 message queue API is the later of the two UNIX message queue APIs.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] It is distinct from the SYS V API, but provides similar function.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The unix man page `mq_overview(7)` provides an overview of POSIX message queues.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] Graphical user interfaces (GUIs) employ a message queue, also called an *event queue* or *input queue*, to pass graphical input actions, such as mouse clicks, keyboard events, or other user inputs, to the application program.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The windowing system places messages indicating user or other events, such as timer ticks or messages sent by other threads, into the message queue.
[src:celery-tasks/message-queue] The GUI application removes these events one at a time by calling a routine called `getNextEvent()` or similar in an event loop, and then calling the appropriate application routine to process that event.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:celery-tasks/task-queue] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Tasks are the building blocks of Celery applications.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A task is a class that can be created out of any callable.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] It performs dual roles in that it defines both what happens when a task is called (sends a message), and what happens when a worker receives that message.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Every task class has a unique name, and this name is referenced in messages so the worker can find the right function to execute.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A task message is not removed from the queue until that message has been acknowledged by a worker.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A worker can reserve many messages in advance and even if the worker is killed – by power failure or some other reason – the message will be redelivered to another worker.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Ideally task functions should be idempotent: meaning the function won’t cause unintended effects even if called multiple times with the same arguments.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Since the worker cannot detect if your tasks are idempotent, the default behavior is to acknowledge the message in advance, just before it’s executed, so that a task invocation that already started is never executed again.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If your task is idempotent you can set the `acks_late` option to have the worker acknowledge the message *after* the task returns instead.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] See also the FAQ entry Should I use retry or acks_late?.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note that the worker will acknowledge the message if the child process executing the task is terminated (either by the task calling `sys.exit()`, or by signal) even when `acks_late` is enabled.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] We assume that a system administrator deliberately killing the task does not want it to automatically restart.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A task that allocates too much memory is in danger of triggering the kernel OOM killer, the same may happen again.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A task that always fails when redelivered may cause a high-frequency message loop taking down the system.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If you really want a task to be redelivered in these scenarios you should consider enabling the `task_reject_on_worker_lost` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A task that blocks indefinitely may eventually stop the worker instance from doing any other work.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Time limits are convenient for making sure all tasks return in a timely manner, but a time limit event will actually kill the process by force so only use them to detect cases where you haven’t used manual timeouts yet.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] In previous versions, the default prefork pool scheduler was not friendly to long-running tasks, so if you had tasks that ran for minutes/hours, it was advised to enable the `-Ofair` command-line argument to the **celery worker**.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] However, as of version 4.0, -Ofair is now the default scheduling strategy.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] See Prefetch Limits for more information, and for the best performance route long-running and short-running tasks to dedicated workers (Automatic routing).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If your worker hangs then please investigate what tasks are running before submitting an issue, as most likely the hanging is caused by one or more tasks hanging on a network operation.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Bound tasks are needed for retries (using `app.Task.retry()`), for accessing information about the current task request, and for any additional functionality you add to custom task base classes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If no explicit name is provided the task decorator will generate one for you, and this name will be based on 1) the module the task is defined in, and 2) the name of the task function.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A best practice is to use the module name as a name-space, this way names won’t collide if there’s already a task with that name defined in another module.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can use the *inspect* command in a worker to view the names of all registered tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] See the *inspect registered* command in the Management Command-line Utilities (inspect/control) section of the User Guide.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] There are some cases when the default automatic naming isn’t suitable.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Using the default automatic naming, each task will have a generated name like *moduleA.tasks.taskA*, *moduleA.tasks.taskB*, *moduleB.tasks.test*, and so on.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You may want to get rid of having *tasks* in all task names.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] As pointed above, you can explicitly give names for all tasks, or you can change the automatic naming behavior by overriding `app.gen_task_name()`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] So each task will have a name like *moduleA.taskA*, *moduleA.taskB* and *moduleB.test*.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Make sure that your `app.gen_task_name()` is a pure function: meaning that for the same input it must always return the same output.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] `app.Task.request` contains information and state related to the currently executing task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The unique id of the task’s group, if this task is a member.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The unique id of the chord this task belongs to (if the task is part of the header).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Custom ID used for things like de-duplication.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] How many times the current task has been retried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Set to `True` if the task is executed locally in the client, not by a worker.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This is in UTC time (depending on the `enable_utc` setting).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The original expiry time of the task (if any).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Node name of the worker instance executing the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Additional message delivery information.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This is a mapping containing the exchange and routing key used to deliver this task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Used by for example `app.Task.retry()` to resend the task to the same destination queue.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Availability of keys in this dict depends on the message broker used.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Name of queue to send replies back to (used with RPC result backend for example).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This flag is set to true if the task wasn’t executed by the worker.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A tuple of the current `(soft, hard)` time limits active for this task (if any).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A list of signatures to be called if this task returns successfully.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A list of signatures to be called if this task fails.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Set to true the caller has UTC enabled (`enable_utc`).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Mapping of message headers sent with this task message (may be `None`).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Usually the same as the task id, often used in amqp to keep track of what a reply is for.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The unique id of the first task in the workflow this task is part of (if any).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The unique id of the task that called this task (if any).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Reversed list of tasks that form a chain (if any).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The last item in this list will be the next task to succeed the current task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If using version one of the task protocol the chain tasks will be in `request.callbacks` instead.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] How many times the task was replaced, if at all.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The `bind` argument means that the function will be a “bound method” so that you can access attributes and methods on the task type instance.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The worker will automatically set up logging for you, or you can configure logging manually.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A special logger is available named “celery.task”, you can inherit from this logger to automatically get the task name and unique id as part of the logs.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Celery uses the standard Python logger library, and the documentation can be found `here`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can also use `print()`, as anything written to standard out/-err will be redirected to the logging system (you can disable this, see `worker_redirect_stdouts`).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The worker won’t update the redirection if you create a logger instance somewhere in your task or task module.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If a specific Celery logger you need is not emitting logs, you should check that the logger is propagating properly.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Sensitive information will still be accessible to anyone able to read your task message from the broker, or otherwise able intercept it.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] For this reason you should probably encrypt your message if it contains sensitive information, or in this example with a credit card number the actual number could be stored encrypted in a secure store that you retrieve and decrypt in the task itself.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] `app.Task.retry()` can be used to re-execute the task, for example in the event of recoverable errors.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When you call `retry` it’ll send a new message, using the same task-id, and it’ll take care to make sure the message is delivered to the same queue as the originating task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When a task is retried this is also recorded as a task state, so that you can track the progress of the task using the result instance (see States).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The `app.Task.retry()` call will raise an exception so any code after the retry won’t be reached.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This is the `Retry` exception, it isn’t handled as an error but rather as a semi-predicate to signify to the worker that the task is to be retried, so that it can store the correct state when a result backend is enabled.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This is normal operation and always happens unless the `throw` argument to retry is set to `False`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The bind argument to the task decorator will give access to `self` (the task type instance).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The `exc` argument is used to pass exception information that’s used in logs, and when storing task results.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Both the exception and the traceback will be available in the task state (if a result backend is enabled).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When a task is to be retried, it can wait for a given amount of time before doing so, and the default delay is defined by the `default_retry_delay` attribute.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note that the unit for setting the delay is in seconds (int or float).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can also provide the *countdown* argument to `retry()` to override this default.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Sometimes you just want to retry a task whenever a particular exception is raised.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If your tasks depend on another service, like making a request to an API, then it’s a good idea to use exponential backoff to avoid overwhelming the service with your requests.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Fortunately, Celery’s automatic retry support makes it easy.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, this exponential backoff will also introduce random jitter to avoid having all the tasks run at the same moment.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] It will also cap the maximum backoff delay to 10 minutes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] All these settings can be customized via options documented below.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If any of these exceptions are raised during the execution of the task, the task will automatically be retried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, no exceptions will be autoretried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Maximum number of retries before giving up.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A value of `None` means task will retry forever.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If this option is set to `True`, autoretries will be delayed following the rules of exponential backoff.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The first retry will have a delay of 1 second, the second retry will have a delay of 2 seconds, the third will delay 4 seconds, the fourth will delay 8 seconds, and so on.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] (However, this delay value is modified by `retry_jitter`, if it is enabled.) If this option is set to a number, it is used as a delay factor.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] For example, if this option is set to `3`, the first retry will delay 3 seconds, the second will delay 6 seconds, the third will delay 12 seconds, the fourth will delay 24 seconds, and so on.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, this option is set to `False`, and autoretries will not be delayed.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If `retry_backoff` is enabled, this option will set a maximum delay in seconds between task autoretries.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, this option is set to `600`, which is 10 minutes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Jitter is used to introduce randomness into exponential backoff delays, to prevent all tasks in the queue from being executed simultaneously.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If this option is set to `True`, the delay value calculated by `retry_backoff` is treated as a maximum, and the actual delay value will be a random number between zero and that maximum.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, this option is set to `True`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This allows to exclude some exceptions that match `autoretry_for` but for which you don’t want a retry.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can use Pydantic to validate and convert arguments as well as serializing results based on typehints by passing `pydantic=True`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Argument validation only covers arguments/return values on the task side.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You still have serialize arguments yourself when invoking a task with `delay()` or `apply_async()`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] `Union[SomeModel, OtherModel]`) or arguments to generics (e.g.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] `list[SomeModel]`) are **not** supported.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] In case you want to support a list or similar types, it is recommended to use `pydantic.RootModel`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Optional parameters or return values are also handled properly.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Return values will only be serialized if the returned model matches the annotation.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If you pass a model instance of a different type, it will *not* be serialized.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] `mypy` should already catch such errors and you should fix your typehints then.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can pass `True` to enable strict model validation.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Pass additional validation context during Pydantic model validation.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The context already includes the application object as `celery_app` and the task name as `celery_task_name` by default.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When serializing a result, pass these additional arguments to `dump_kwargs()`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] By default, only `mode='json'` is passed.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The task decorator can take a number of options that change the way the task behaves, for example you can set the rate limit for a task using the `rate_limit` option.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Any keyword argument passed to the task decorator will actually be set as an attribute of the resulting task class, and this is a list of the built-in attributes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can set this name manually, or a name will be automatically generated using the module and class name.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If the task is being executed this will contain information about the current request.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Only applies if the task calls `self.retry` or if the task is decorated with the autoretry_for argument.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The maximum number of attempted retries before giving up.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If the number of retries exceeds this value a `MaxRetriesExceededError` exception will be raised.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You have to call `retry()` manually, as it won’t automatically retry on exception..
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A value of `None` will disable the retry limit and the task will retry forever until it succeeds.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Optional tuple of expected error classes that shouldn’t be regarded as an actual error.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Errors in this list will be reported as a failure to the result backend, but the worker won’t log the event as an error, and no traceback will be included.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Default time in seconds before a retry of the task should be executed.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Set the rate limit for this task type (limits the number of tasks that can be run in a given time frame).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Tasks will still complete when a rate limit is in effect, but it may take some time before it’s allowed to start.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If this is `None` no rate limit is in effect.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If it is an integer or float, it is interpreted as “tasks per second”.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The rate limits can be specified in seconds, minutes or hours by appending *“/s”*, *“/m”* or *“/h”* to the value.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Tasks will be evenly distributed over the specified time frame.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Example: *“100/m”* (hundred tasks a minute).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This will enforce a minimum delay of 600ms between starting two tasks on the same worker instance.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Default is the `task_default_rate_limit` setting: if not specified means rate limiting for tasks is disabled by default.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note that this is a *per worker instance* rate limit, and not a global rate limit.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] To enforce a global rate limit (e.g., for an API with a maximum number of requests per second), you must restrict to a given queue.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The hard time limit, in seconds, for this task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When not set the workers default is used.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note that this means you can’t use `AsyncResult` to check if the task is ready, or get its return value.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note: Certain features will not work if task results are disabled.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] For more details check the Canvas documentation.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If `True`, errors will be stored even if the task is configured to ignore results.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Changed in version 5.7: Previously, if the `ignore_result` key was missing from the request message, `store_errors` would default to `True`, ignoring the task’s own `ignore_result` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The worker now correctly falls back to `Task.ignore_result` when no per-request override is present.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A string identifying the default serialization method to use.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Defaults to the `task_serializer` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Can be *pickle*, *json*, *yaml*, or any custom serialization methods that have been registered with `kombu.serialization.registry`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Please see Serializers for more information.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A string identifying the default compression scheme to use.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Defaults to the `task_compression` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Can be *gzip*, or *bzip2*, or any custom compression schemes that have been registered with the `kombu.compression` registry.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Please see Compression for more information.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The result store backend to use for this task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] An instance of one of the backend classes in *celery.backends*.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Defaults to *app.backend*, defined by the `result_backend` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If set to `True` messages for this task will be acknowledged **after** the task has been executed, not *just before* (the default behavior).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Note: This means the task may be executed multiple times should the worker crash in the middle of execution.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The global default can be overridden by the `task_acks_late` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If `True` the task will report its status as “started” when the task is executed by a worker.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The default value is `False` as the normal behavior is to not report that level of granularity.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Tasks are either pending, finished, or waiting to be retried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Having a “started” status can be useful for when there are long running tasks and there’s a need to report what task is currently running.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The global default can be overridden by the `task_track_started` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Celery can keep track of the tasks current state.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The state also contains the result of a successful task, or the exception and traceback information of a failed task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] There are several *result backends* to choose from, and they all have different strengths and weaknesses (see Result Backends).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] During its lifetime a task will transition through several possible states, and each state may have arbitrary meta-data attached to it.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] When a task moves into a new state the previous state is forgotten about, but some transitions can be deduced, (e.g., a task now in the `FAILED` state, is implied to have been in the `STARTED` state at some point).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] There are also sets of states, like the set of `FAILURE_STATES`, and the set of `READY_STATES`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The client uses the membership of these sets to decide whether the exception should be re-raised (`PROPAGATE_STATES`), or whether the state can be cached (it can if the task is ready).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] If you want to keep track of tasks or need the return values, then Celery must store or send the states somewhere so that they can be retrieved later.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] There are several built-in result backends to choose from: SQLAlchemy/Django ORM, Memcached, RabbitMQ/QPid (`rpc`), and Redis – or you can define your own.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] No backend works well for every use case.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You should read about the strengths and weaknesses of each backend, and choose the most appropriate for your needs.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Backends use resources to store and transmit results.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] To ensure that resources are released, you must eventually call `get()` or `forget()` on EVERY `AsyncResult` instance returned after calling a task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The RPC result backend (*rpc://*) is special as it doesn’t actually *store* the states, but rather sends them as messages.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This is an important difference as it means that a result *can only be retrieved once*, and *only by the client that initiated the task*.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Two different processes can’t wait for the same result.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Even with that limitation, it is an excellent choice if you need to receive state changes in real-time.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Using messaging means the client doesn’t have to poll for new states.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The messages are transient (non-persistent) by default, so the results will disappear if the broker restarts.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can configure the result backend to send persistent messages using the `result_persistent` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Keeping state in the database can be convenient for many, especially for web applications with a database already in place, but it also comes with limitations.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Task is waiting for execution or unknown.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Any task id that’s not known is implied to be in the pending state.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Not reported by default, to enable please see `app.Task.track_started`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] You can easily define your own states, all you need is a unique name.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The name of the state is usually an uppercase string.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] As an example you could have a look at the `abortable tasks` which defines a custom `ABORTED` state.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Use `update_state()` to update a task’s state:.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Here I created the state *“PROGRESS”*, telling any application aware of this state that the task is currently in progress, and also where it is in the process by having *current* and *total* counts as part of the state meta-data.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] This can then be used to create progress bars for example.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] A rarely known Python fact is that exceptions must conform to some simple rules to support being serialized by the pickle module.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] Tasks that raise exceptions that aren’t pickleable won’t work properly when Pickle is used as the serializer.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] To make sure that your exceptions are pickleable the exception *MUST* provide the original arguments it was instantiated with in its `.args` attribute.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p01] The simplest way to ensure this is to have the exception call `Exception.__init__`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The worker wraps the task in a tracing function that records the final state of the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] There are a number of exceptions that can be used to signal this function to change how it treats the return of the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The task may raise `Ignore` to force the worker to ignore the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This means that no state will be recorded for the task, but the message is still acknowledged (removed from queue).
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This can be used if you want to implement custom revoke-like functionality, or manually store the result of a task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The task may raise `Reject` to reject the task message using AMQPs `basic_reject` method.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This won’t have any effect unless `Task.acks_late` is enabled.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Rejecting a message has the same effect as acking it, but some brokers may implement additional functionality that can be used.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] For example RabbitMQ supports the concept of Dead Letter Exchanges where a queue can be configured to use a dead letter exchange that rejected messages are redelivered to.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Reject can also be used to re-queue messages, but please be very careful when using this as it can easily result in an infinite message loop.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Consult your broker documentation for more details about the `basic_reject` method.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The `Retry` exception is raised by the `Task.retry` method to tell the worker that the task is being retried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] All tasks inherit from the `app.Task` class.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The `run()` method becomes the task body.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] A task is **not** instantiated for every request, but is registered in the task registry as a global instance.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This means that the `__init__` constructor will only be called once per process, and that the task class is semantically closer to an Actor.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] And you route every request to the same process, then it will keep state between requests.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The `db` attribute of the `process_rows` task will then always stay the same in each process.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You can also use your custom class in your whole Celery app by passing it as the `task_cls` argument when instantiating the app.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This will make all your tasks declared using the decorator syntax within your app to use your `DatabaseTask` class and will all have a `db` attribute.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The default value is the class provided by Celery: `'celery.app.task:Task'`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Task handlers are methods that execute at specific points in a task’s lifecycle.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] All handlers run **synchronously** within the same worker process and thread that executes the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Run by the worker before the task starts executing.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This handler **blocks** the task: the `run()` method will *not* begin until `before_start` returns.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The return value of this handler is ignored.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Run by the worker if the task executes successfully.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Invoked **after** the task result has already been persisted in the result backend.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] External clients may observe the task as `SUCCESS` while this handler is still running.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Run by the worker when the task is to be retried.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Invoked **after** the task state has been updated to `RETRY` in the result backend but **before** the retry is scheduled.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Invoked **after** the task result has already been persisted in the result backend with `FAILURE` state.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] External clients may observe the task as failed while this handler is still running.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Executes after the outcome-specific handler when the task reaches a terminal state.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] In practice, this means it runs after `on_success` or `on_failure`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] It is not executed for `RETRY`, `REJECTED`, or `IGNORED` states.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] If a hook is needed for every attempt, consider using the `task_postrun` signal.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Upon receiving a message to run a task, the worker creates a `request` to represent such demand.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Custom task classes may override which request class to use by changing the attribute `celery.app.task.Task.Request`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You may either assign the custom request class itself, or its fully qualified name.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The request has several responsibilities.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Custom request classes should cover them all – they are responsible to actually run and trace the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] We strongly recommend to inherit from `celery.worker.request.Request`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] When using the pre-forking worker, the methods `on_timeout()` and `on_failure()` are executed in the main worker process.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] An application may leverage such facility to detect failures which are not detected using `celery.app.task.Task.on_failure()`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] As an example, the following custom request detects and logs hard time limits, and other failures.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This part isn’t something you need to know, but you may be interested.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] All defined tasks are listed in a registry.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The registry contains a list of task names and their task classes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This is the list of tasks built into Celery.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Note that tasks will only be registered when the module they’re defined in is imported.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The default loader imports any modules listed in the `imports` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The `app.task()` decorator is responsible for registering your task in the applications task registry.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] When tasks are sent, no actual function code is sent with it, just the name of the task to execute.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] When the worker then receives the message it can look up the name in its task registry to find the execution code.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This means that your workers should always be updated with the same software as the client.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This is a drawback, but the alternative is a technical challenge that’s yet to be solved.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] If you don’t care about the results of a task, be sure to set the `ignore_result` option, as storing results wastes time and resources.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Results can even be disabled globally using the `task_ignore_result` setting.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Results can be enabled/disabled on a per-execution basis, by passing the `ignore_result` boolean parameter, when calling `apply_async`.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] By default tasks will *not ignore results* (`ignore_result=False`) when a result backend is configured.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You find additional optimization tips in the Optimizing Guide.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Having a task wait for the result of another task is really inefficient, and may even cause a deadlock if the worker pool is exhausted.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Make your design asynchronous instead, for example by using *callbacks*.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Here I instead created a chain of tasks by linking together different `signature()`’s.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You can read about chains and other powerful constructs at Canvas: Designing Work-flows.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] By default Celery will not allow you to run subtasks synchronously within a task, but in rare or extreme cases you might need to do so.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] **WARNING**: enabling subtasks to run synchronously is not recommended!
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The task granularity is the amount of computation needed by each subtask.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] In general it is better to split the problem up into many small tasks rather than have a few long running tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] With smaller tasks you can process more tasks in parallel and the tasks won’t run long enough to block the worker from processing other waiting tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] However, executing a task does have overhead.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] A message needs to be sent, data may not be local, etc.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] So if the tasks are too fine-grained the overhead added probably removes any benefit.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The book Art of Concurrency has a section dedicated to the topic of task granularity [AOC1].
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Section 2.2.1, “The Art of Concurrency”.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The worker processing the task should be as close to the data as possible.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The best would be to have a copy in memory, the worst would be a full transfer from another continent.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] If the data is far away, you could try to run another worker at location, or if that’s not possible - cache often used data, or preload data you know is going to be used.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The easiest way to share data between workers is to use a distributed cache system, like memcached.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The paper Distributed Computing Economics by Jim Gray is an excellent introduction to the topic of data locality.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Since Celery is a distributed system, you can’t know which process, or on what machine the task will be executed.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You can’t even know if the task will run in a timely manner.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] The ancient async sayings tells us that “asserting the world is the responsibility of the task”.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] They shouldn’t be passed on as arguments to tasks.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] It’s almost always better to re-fetch the object from the database when the task is running instead, as using old data may lead to race conditions.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Now, the queue is very busy, so the task won’t be run for another 2 minutes.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] In the meantime another author makes changes to the article, so when the task is finally run, the body of the article is reverted to the old version because the task had the old body in its argument.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] There might even be performance benefits to this approach, as sending large messages may be expensive.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This is a Django view creating an article object in the database, then passing the primary key to a task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] It uses the *transaction.atomic* decorator, that will commit the transaction when the view returns, or roll back if the view raises an exception.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] There is a race condition because transactions are atomic.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] This means the article object is not persisted to the database until after the view function returns a response.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] If the asynchronous task starts executing before the transaction is committed, it may attempt to query the article object before it exists.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] To prevent this, we need to ensure that the transaction is committed before triggering the task.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] It’s a shortcut that uses Django’s `on_commit` callback to launch your Celery task once all transactions have been committed successfully.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] `on_commit` is available in Django 1.9 and above, if you are using a version prior to that then the django-transaction-hooks library adds support for this.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Let’s take a real world example: a blog where comments posted need to be filtered for spam.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] When the comment is created, the spam filter runs in the background, so the user doesn’t have to wait for it to finish.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] I have a Django blog application allowing comments on blog posts.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] I’ll describe parts of the models/views and tasks for this application.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] In the view where the comment is posted, I first write the comment to the database, then I launch the spam filter task in the background.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] To filter spam in comments I use Akismet, the service used to filter spam in comments posted to the free blog platform *Wordpress*.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] Akismet is free for personal use, but for commercial use you need to pay.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] You have to sign up to their service to get an API key.
[src:celery-tasks/userguide-tasks-p02] To make API calls to Akismet I use the akismet.py library written by Michael Foord.
